356/* check_myhostname - lookup hostname and validate */
357
358static const char *check_myhostname(void)
359{
360 static const char *name;
361 const char *dot;
362 const char *domain;
363
364 /*
365 * Use cached result.
366 */
367 if (name)
368 return (name);
369
370 /*
371 * If the local machine name is not in FQDN form, try to append the
372 * contents of $mydomain. Use a default domain as a final workaround.
373 *
374 * DO NOT CALL GETHOSTBYNAME OR GETNAMEINFO HERE - IT MAKES EVERY POSTFIX
375 * PROGRAM HANG WHEN DNS SERVICE IS UNAVAILABLE. IF YOU DON'T LIKE THE
376 * DEFAULT, THEN EDIT MAIN.CF.
377 */
378 name = get_hostname();
379 /* DO NOT CALL GETHOSTBYNAME OR GETNAMEINFO HERE - EDIT MAIN.CF */
380 if ((dot = strchr(name, '.')) == 0) {
381 /* DO NOT CALL GETHOSTBYNAME OR GETNAMEINFO HERE - EDIT MAIN.CF */
382 if ((domain = mail_conf_lookup_eval(VAR_MYDOMAIN)) == 0)
383 domain = DEF_MYDOMAIN;
384 /* DO NOT CALL GETHOSTBYNAME OR GETNAMEINFO HERE - EDIT MAIN.CF */
385 name = concatenate(name, ".", domain, (char *) 0);
386 }
387 /* DO NOT CALL GETHOSTBYNAME OR GETNAMEINFO HERE - EDIT MAIN.CF */
388 return (name);
389}
390
391/* check_mydomainname - lookup domain name and validate */
392
393static const char *check_mydomainname(void)
394{
395 char *dot;
396
397 /*
398 * Use a default domain when the hostname is not a FQDN ("foo").
399 *
400 * DO NOT CALL GETHOSTBYNAME OR GETNAMEINFO HERE - IT MAKES EVERY POSTFIX
401 * PROGRAM HANG WHEN DNS SERVICE IS UNAVAILABLE. IF YOU DON'T LIKE THE
402 * DEFAULT, THEN EDIT MAIN.CF.
403 */
404 /* DO NOT CALL GETHOSTBYNAME OR GETNAMEINFO HERE - EDIT MAIN.CF */
405 if ((dot = strchr(var_myhostname, '.')) == 0)
406 /* DO NOT CALL GETHOSTBYNAME OR GETNAMEINFO HERE - EDIT MAIN.CF */
407 return (DEF_MYDOMAIN);
408 /* DO NOT CALL GETHOSTBYNAME OR GETNAMEINFO HERE - EDIT MAIN.CF */
409 return (dot + 1);
410}

412/* check_default_privs - lookup default user attributes and validate */
413
414static void check_default_privs(void)
415{
416 struct passwd *pwd;
417
418 if ((pwd = getpwnam(var_default_privs)) == 0)
419 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: unknown user name value: %s",
420 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
421 VAR_DEFAULT_PRIVS, var_default_privs);
422 if ((var_default_uid = pwd->pw_uid) == 0)
423 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: user %s has privileged user ID",
424 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
425 VAR_DEFAULT_PRIVS, var_default_privs);
426 if ((var_default_gid = pwd->pw_gid) == 0)
427 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: user %s has privileged group ID",
428 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
429 VAR_DEFAULT_PRIVS, var_default_privs);
430}
431
432/* check_mail_owner - lookup owner user attributes and validate */
433
434static void check_mail_owner(void)
435{
436 struct passwd *pwd;
437
438 if ((pwd = getpwnam(var_mail_owner)) == 0)
439 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: unknown user name value: %s",
440 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
441 VAR_MAIL_OWNER, var_mail_owner);
442 if ((var_owner_uid = pwd->pw_uid) == 0)
443 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: user %s has privileged user ID",
444 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
445 VAR_MAIL_OWNER, var_mail_owner);
446 if ((var_owner_gid = pwd->pw_gid) == 0)
447 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: user %s has privileged group ID",
448 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
449 VAR_MAIL_OWNER, var_mail_owner);
450
451 /*
452 * This detects only some forms of sharing. Enumerating the entire
453 * password file name space could be expensive. The purpose of this code
454 * is to discourage user ID sharing by developers and package
455 * maintainers.
456 */
457 if ((pwd = getpwuid(var_owner_uid)) != 0
458 && strcmp(pwd->pw_name, var_mail_owner) != 0)
459 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: user %s has same user ID as %s",
460 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
461 VAR_MAIL_OWNER, var_mail_owner, pwd->pw_name);
462}
463
464/* check_sgid_group - lookup setgid group attributes and validate */
465
466static void check_sgid_group(void)
467{
468 struct group *grp;
469
470 if ((grp = getgrnam(var_sgid_group)) == 0)
471 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: unknown group name: %s",
472 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
473 VAR_SGID_GROUP, var_sgid_group);
474 if ((var_sgid_gid = grp->gr_gid) == 0)
475 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: group %s has privileged group ID",
476 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
477 VAR_SGID_GROUP, var_sgid_group);
478
479 /*
480 * This detects only some forms of sharing. Enumerating the entire group
481 * file name space could be expensive. The purpose of this code is to
482 * discourage group ID sharing by developers and package maintainers.
483 */
484 if ((grp = getgrgid(var_sgid_gid)) != 0
485 && strcmp(grp->gr_name, var_sgid_group) != 0)
486 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: group %s has same group ID as %s",
487 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
488 VAR_SGID_GROUP, var_sgid_group, grp->gr_name);
489}
490
491/* check_overlap - disallow UID or GID sharing */
492
493static void check_overlap(void)
494{
495 if (strcmp(var_default_privs, var_mail_owner) == 0)
496 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameters %s and %s specify the same user %s",
497 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
498 VAR_DEFAULT_PRIVS, VAR_MAIL_OWNER,
499 var_default_privs);
500 if (var_default_uid == var_owner_uid)
501 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameters %s and %s: users %s and %s have the same user ID: %ld",
502 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
503 VAR_DEFAULT_PRIVS, VAR_MAIL_OWNER,
504 var_default_privs, var_mail_owner,
505 (long) var_owner_uid);
506 if (var_default_gid == var_owner_gid)
507 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameters %s and %s: users %s and %s have the same group ID: %ld",
508 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
509 VAR_DEFAULT_PRIVS, VAR_MAIL_OWNER,
510 var_default_privs, var_mail_owner,
511 (long) var_owner_gid);
512 if (var_default_gid == var_sgid_gid)
513 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameters %s and %s: user %s and group %s have the same group ID: %ld",
514 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
515 VAR_DEFAULT_PRIVS, VAR_SGID_GROUP,
516 var_default_privs, var_sgid_group,
517 (long) var_sgid_gid);
518 if (var_owner_gid == var_sgid_gid)
519 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameters %s and %s: user %s and group %s have the same group ID: %ld",
520 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
521 VAR_MAIL_OWNER, VAR_SGID_GROUP,
522 var_mail_owner, var_sgid_group,
523 (long) var_sgid_gid);
524}

528/* read_param_from_file - read parameter value from file */
529
530static char *read_param_from_file(const char *path)
531{
532 VSTRING *why = vstring_alloc(100);
533 VSTRING *buf = vstring_alloc(100);
534 VSTREAM *fp;
535 char *bp;
536 char *result;
537
538 /*
539 * Ugly macros to make complex expressions less unreadable.
540 */
541#define SKIP(start, var, cond) do { \
542 for (var = start; *var && (cond); var++) \
543 /* void */; \
544 } while (0)
545
546#define TRIM(s) do { \
547 char *p; \
548 for (p = (s) + strlen(s); p > (s) && ISSPACE(p[-1]); p--) \
549 /* void */; \
550 *p = 0; \
551 } while (0)
552
553 fp = safe_open(path, O_RDONLY, 0, (struct stat *) 0, -1, -1, why);
554 if (fp == 0)
555 msg_fatal("%s: %s", path, vstring_str(why));
556 vstring_get_nonl(buf, fp);
557 if (vstream_ferror(fp)) /* FIX 20070501 */
558 msg_fatal("%s: read error: %m", path);
559 vstream_fclose(fp);
560 SKIP(vstring_str(buf), bp, ISSPACE(*bp));
561 TRIM(bp);
562 result = mystrdup(bp);
563
564 vstring_free(why);
565 vstring_free(buf);
566 return (result);
567}
568
569#endif

571/* check_legacy_defaults - flag parameters that require safety-net logging */
572
573static void check_legacy_defaults(void)
574{
575
576 /*
577 * Basic idea: when an existing parameter default is changed, or a new
578 * parameter is introduced with incompatible default behavior, force
579 * Postfix to run with backwards-compatible default settings and log a
580 * warning when the backwards-compatible behavior is used.
581 *
582 * Based on a review of Postfix logging the system administrator can decide
583 * whether or not to make backwards-compatible default settings permanent
584 * in main.cf or master.cf.
585 *
586 * To turn off further warnings and deploy the new default settings, the
587 * system administrator should update the compatibility_level setting as
588 * recommended in the RELEASE_NOTES file.
589 *
590 * Each incompatible change has its own flag variable, instead of bit in a
591 * shared variable. We don't want to rip up code when we need more flag
592 * bits.
593 */
594
595 /*
596 * Look for specific parameters whose default changed when the
597 * compatibility level changed to 2.
598 */
599 if (var_compat_level < 2) {
600 if (mail_conf_lookup(VAR_RELAY_DOMAINS) == 0) {
601 warn_compat_break_relay_domains = 1;
602 if (mail_conf_lookup(VAR_FFLUSH_DOMAINS) == 0)
603 warn_compat_break_flush_domains = 1;
604 }
605 if (mail_conf_lookup(VAR_MYNETWORKS) == 0
606 && mail_conf_lookup(VAR_MYNETWORKS_STYLE) == 0)
607 warn_compat_break_mynetworks_style = 1;
608 }
609
610 /*
611 * Look for specific parameters whose default changed when the
612 * compatibility level changed from 0 to 1.
613 */
614 if (var_compat_level < 1) {
615 if (mail_conf_lookup(VAR_APP_DOT_MYDOMAIN) == 0)
616 warn_compat_break_app_dot_mydomain = 1;
617
618 /*
619 * Not: #ifndef NO_EAI. They must configure SMTPUTF8_ENABLE=no if a
620 * warning message is logged, so that they don't suddenly start to
621 * lose mail after Postfix is built with EAI support.
622 */
623 if (mail_conf_lookup(VAR_SMTPUTF8_ENABLE) == 0)
624 warn_compat_break_smtputf8_enable = 1;
625 warn_compat_break_chroot = 1;
626 }
627}

629/* mail_params_init - configure built-in parameters */
630
631void mail_params_init()
632{
633 static const CONFIG_INT_TABLE first_int_defaults[] = {
634 VAR_COMPAT_LEVEL, DEF_COMPAT_LEVEL, &var_compat_level, 0, 0,
635 0,
636 };
637 static const CONFIG_STR_TABLE first_str_defaults[] = {
638 /* $mail_version may appear in other parameters. */
639 VAR_MAIL_VERSION, DEF_MAIL_VERSION, &var_mail_version, 1, 0,
640 VAR_SYSLOG_FACILITY, DEF_SYSLOG_FACILITY, &var_syslog_facility, 1, 0,
641 VAR_INET_PROTOCOLS, DEF_INET_PROTOCOLS, &var_inet_protocols, 0, 0,
642 VAR_MULTI_CONF_DIRS, DEF_MULTI_CONF_DIRS, &var_multi_conf_dirs, 0, 0,
643 /* multi_instance_wrapper may have dependencies but not dependents. */
644 VAR_MULTI_GROUP, DEF_MULTI_GROUP, &var_multi_group, 0, 0,
645 VAR_MULTI_NAME, DEF_MULTI_NAME, &var_multi_name, 0, 0,
646 0,
647 };
648 static const CONFIG_BOOL_TABLE first_bool_defaults[] = {

781 const char *cp;
782
783 /*
784 * Extract compatibility level first, so that we can determine what
785 * parameters of interest are left at their legacy defaults.
786 */
787 get_mail_conf_int_table(first_int_defaults);
788 check_legacy_defaults();
789
790 /*
791 * Extract syslog_facility early, so that from here on all errors are
792 * logged with the proper facility.
793 */
794 get_mail_conf_str_table(first_str_defaults);
795
796 if (!msg_syslog_facility(var_syslog_facility))
797 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: unrecognized value: %s",
798 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
799 VAR_SYSLOG_FACILITY, var_syslog_facility);
800
801 /*
802 * Should daemons terminate after table open error, or should they
803 * continue execution with reduced functionality?
804 */
805 get_mail_conf_bool_table(first_bool_defaults);
806 if (var_daemon_open_fatal)
807 dict_allow_surrogate = 0;
808
809 /*
810 * Should we open tables with UTF8 support, or in the legacy 8-bit clean
811 * mode with ASCII-only casefolding?
812 */
813 get_mail_conf_nbool_table(first_nbool_defaults);
814
815 /*
816 * Report run-time versus compile-time discrepancies.
817 */
818#ifdef NO_EAI
819 if (var_smtputf8_enable)
820 msg_warn("%s is true, but EAI support is not compiled in",
821 VAR_SMTPUTF8_ENABLE);
822 var_smtputf8_enable = 0;
823#endif
824 util_utf8_enable = var_smtputf8_enable;
825
826 /*
827 * What protocols should we attempt to support? The result is stored in
828 * the global inet_proto_table variable.
829 */
830 (void) inet_proto_init(VAR_INET_PROTOCOLS, var_inet_protocols);
831
832 /*
833 * Variables whose defaults are determined at runtime. Some sites use
834 * short hostnames in the host table; some sites name their system after
835 * the domain.
836 */
837 get_mail_conf_str_fn_table(function_str_defaults);
838 if (!valid_hostname(var_myhostname, DO_GRIPE))
839 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: bad parameter value: %s",
840 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
841 VAR_MYHOSTNAME, var_myhostname);
842 if (!valid_hostname(var_mydomain, DO_GRIPE))
843 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameter %s: bad parameter value: %s",
844 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
845 VAR_MYDOMAIN, var_mydomain);
846
847 /*
848 * Variables that are needed by almost every program.
849 *
850 * XXX Reading the myorigin value from file is originally a Debian Linux
851 * feature. This code is not enabled by default because of problems: 1)
852 * it re-implements its own parameter syntax checks, and 2) it does not
853 * implement $name expansions.
854 */
855 get_mail_conf_str_table(other_str_defaults);
856#ifdef MYORIGIN_FROM_FILE
857 if (*var_myorigin == '/') {
858 char *origin = read_param_from_file(var_myorigin);
859
860 if (*origin == 0)
861 msg_fatal("%s file %s is empty", VAR_MYORIGIN, var_myorigin);
862 myfree(var_myorigin); /* FIX 20070501 */
863 var_myorigin = origin;
864 }
865#endif
866 get_mail_conf_int_table(other_int_defaults);
867 get_mail_conf_long_table(long_defaults);
868 get_mail_conf_bool_table(bool_defaults);
869 get_mail_conf_time_table(time_defaults);
870 check_default_privs();
871 check_mail_owner();
872 check_sgid_group();
873 check_overlap();
874 dict_db_cache_size = var_db_read_buf;
875 dict_lmdb_map_size = var_lmdb_map_size;
876 inet_windowsize = var_inet_windowsize;
877
878 /*
879 * Variables whose defaults are determined at runtime, after other
880 * variables have been set. This dependency is admittedly a bit tricky.
881 * XXX Perhaps we should just register variables, and let the evaluator
882 * figure out in what order to evaluate things.
883 */
884 get_mail_conf_str_fn_table(function_str_defaults_2);
885
886 /*
887 * FIX 200412 The IPv6 patch did not call own_inet_addr_list() before
888 * entering the chroot jail on Linux IPv6 systems. Linux has the IPv6
889 * interface list in /proc, which is not available after chrooting.
890 */
891 (void) own_inet_addr_list();
892
893 /*
894 * The PID variable cannot be set from the configuration file!!
895 */
896 set_mail_conf_int(VAR_PID, var_pid = getpid());
897
898 /*
899 * Neither can the start time variable. It isn't even visible.
900 */
901 time(&var_starttime);
902
903 /*
904 * Export the syslog name so children can inherit and use it before they
905 * have initialized.
906 */
907 if ((cp = safe_getenv(CONF_ENV_LOGTAG)) == 0
908 || strcmp(cp, var_syslog_name) != 0)
909 if (setenv(CONF_ENV_LOGTAG, var_syslog_name, 1) < 0)
910 msg_fatal("setenv %s %s: %m", CONF_ENV_LOGTAG, var_syslog_name);
911
912 /*
913 * I have seen this happen just too often.
914 */
915 if (strcasecmp_utf8(var_myhostname, var_relayhost) == 0)
916 msg_fatal("%s and %s parameter settings must not be identical: %s",
917 VAR_MYHOSTNAME, VAR_RELAYHOST, var_myhostname);
918
919 /*
920 * XXX These should be caught by a proper parameter parsing algorithm.
921 */
922 if (var_myorigin[strcspn(var_myorigin, CHARS_COMMA_SP)])
923 msg_fatal("%s parameter setting must not contain multiple values: %s",
924 VAR_MYORIGIN, var_myorigin);
925
926 if (var_relayhost[strcspn(var_relayhost, CHARS_COMMA_SP)])
927 msg_fatal("%s parameter setting must not contain multiple values: %s",
928 VAR_RELAYHOST, var_relayhost);
929
930 /*
931 * One more sanity check.
932 */
933 if ((cp = verp_delims_verify(var_verp_delims)) != 0)
934 msg_fatal("file %s/%s: parameters %s and %s: %s",
935 var_config_dir, MAIN_CONF_FILE,
936 VAR_VERP_DELIMS, VAR_VERP_FILTER, cp);
937}
